00:00.000 --> 00:13.200
In order to make an investment decision, we will need to familiarize ourselves with the four basic rules that are applied in this process

00:13.200 --> 00:19.600
The first rule is related to the pure given value, abbreviated as NPV

00:19.600 --> 00:24.800
Next, the Internal Revenue Rate, IRR

00:24.800 --> 00:28.600
Next, the profitability index and the period of purchase

00:29.200 --> 00:37.000
The last two parameters are familiar to us from the standard procedures of the economic analysis of the enterprise

00:37.000 --> 00:42.600
But they are used with an amendment to the discount

00:42.600 --> 00:52.800
The first two, NPV and IRR, are entirely and completely built on the model of assessing the value of a financial asset

00:53.400 --> 00:58.800
We will also consider a couple of points in this section, but more on that later

00:58.800 --> 01:17.200
So, the pure given value, abbreviated as NPV, is the difference between the discounted investments in the project and the discounted cash flows from the project

01:17.600 --> 01:32.400
Remember, when we work in the standard economy, when we operate with accounting, we take the expenses per nominal and the income per nominal, and find the difference

01:32.400 --> 01:40.800
In our case, we use the expenses and income in the same way, but only after the discount

01:41.400 --> 01:50.200
So, if you discount, returning to the example of determining your value

01:50.200 --> 02:03.200
If you discount all your expenses that you will have to make in the next year, and all your income that you will have to get in the next year

02:03.600 --> 02:16.200
You will get two numbers, then subtract the expenses from the income, you will get a difference, either positive or negative

02:16.200 --> 02:26.200
And this will be evidence that you have income for this year, or vice versa, you do not have it and you will be in debt to someone

02:27.200 --> 02:32.200
Let's go back to our slide. The rules of using NPV

02:32.200 --> 02:40.600
You can accept a project for execution, for financing, if the NPV is greater than zero

02:40.600 --> 02:47.200
You can, if you have several projects, accept a project for execution, whose NPV is the largest

02:47.200 --> 02:49.200
These are simple rules

02:49.200 --> 02:55.200
But I would like to ask you a question. What if the NPV project is zero?

02:55.200 --> 02:59.200
Should you accept such a project for execution, if there are no others?

02:59.200 --> 03:04.200
There are situations when such a project can be accepted for execution. Why?

03:04.200 --> 03:10.200
Because thanks to such a project, you can save your capital

03:11.200 --> 03:18.200
Your capital will not decrease, but it will not grow. It will remain at the same level, and this is already an achievement

03:18.200 --> 03:22.200
You were able to save it over the past year, not lose it

03:22.200 --> 03:27.200
So in some cases, a project with a zero NPV can be accepted

03:27.200 --> 03:37.200
At the same time, I will draw your attention to the fact that a project with a zero NPV will certainly have an accounting profit

03:37.200 --> 03:44.200
Let's look at a more detailed example. The following slide shows the calculations

03:44.200 --> 03:50.200
So, the investment in the project is 100 units

03:50.200 --> 03:56.200
Let's assume that these investments are made at once, at the current time

03:56.200 --> 04:02.200
They do not need to be discounted. At the current time. We do this to make the example easier

04:02.200 --> 04:14.200
The project is designed for 5 years, and its cash flows are 20, 20, 20, 30 and 30 units

04:14.200 --> 04:23.200
If we add them up by the nominal, we get a profit of 120 minus 100, the income is certainly higher than the expenses

04:23.200 --> 04:30.200
The discount rate is 10%, in other words, the market value of the resources is 10%

04:31.200 --> 04:43.200
Then we substitute everything in the formula. NPV, we take the investment in the project with a minus sign, because it is the cash flow

04:43.200 --> 04:49.200
Everything else we take with a plus sign, because it is the inflow of cash

04:49.200 --> 04:57.200
Please note that the discount rate is not in percents, but in dollars

04:57.200 --> 05:06.200
So, if we calculate by this formula, for example, a computer or Excel can do it very quickly

05:06.200 --> 05:12.200
Then we get that NPV is equal to, look, the second line

05:12.200 --> 05:19.200
20 units of income received a year later today cost us 18 kopecks

05:19.200 --> 05:26.200
20 units of income received two years later today cost us 16 kopecks

05:26.200 --> 05:38.200
Then 15 and income of 30 units per year we turn into today's 20 and 18

05:38.200 --> 05:45.200
If we add them all up, we get only 88, almost 89 units

05:45.200 --> 05:53.200
This is not enough to get to zero NPV, we get a negative NPV

05:53.200 --> 06:04.200
In fact, if we take up the implementation of this project, and even if we successfully implement it, we will incur a financial loss of 11 units

06:04.200 --> 06:06.200
This is an absolute value

06:06.200 --> 06:18.200
In the absence of other information, we can say that this project should be rejected

06:19.200 --> 06:24.200
The next rule is related to the so-called period of payback

06:24.200 --> 06:33.200
This is a period that is required to reimburse investment, but taking into account the discounting procedure

06:33.200 --> 06:37.200
Let's look at an example, it is shown on the slide

06:37.200 --> 06:45.200
The same initial 100 units of investment, the same 5 years for which the project is designed

06:46.200 --> 06:56.200
If we take the already discounted cash flows, let them be equal to 25, 25, 25, 25 and 30

06:56.200 --> 07:00.200
4 times 25, the last year 30 units

07:00.200 --> 07:05.200
And check the NPV, yes, there are 30 units

07:05.200 --> 07:14.200
Now about the period of payback, our initial 100 units will pay off exactly in the first 4 years

07:14.200 --> 07:17.200
There is no formula, everything is quite obvious

07:17.200 --> 07:23.200
You add up the cash flows until the amount does not exceed the initial investment

07:23.200 --> 07:34.200
If our investment amount was not 100 units, but 110, what would be the period of payback?

07:35.200 --> 07:37.200
Now the answer

07:37.200 --> 07:45.200
In order to get the required amount of 110 units, we will have to wait 4 years

07:45.200 --> 07:50.200
25, 25, 25, 25, 100, and we need 110

07:50.200 --> 07:58.200
4 years with the last 5 years will bring us 30 units of income

07:59.200 --> 08:05.200
We need to get 10 more units of income to pay back the investment

08:05.200 --> 08:08.200
Therefore, it is 1 third of the amount

08:08.200 --> 08:18.200
Thus, we can say that the period of payback in this case will be 4.1 years

08:18.200 --> 08:24.200
The next rule is the use of the profitability index

08:24.200 --> 08:30.200
The profitability index is almost the same as the NPV, but expressed in percents

08:30.200 --> 08:42.200
If we found a difference between the investment in the project and the income from the project

08:43.200 --> 08:53.200
In this case, we need to find the relationship between the two amounts

08:53.200 --> 08:56.200
You can see an example here

08:56.200 --> 09:07.200
If the income from the project is 130 units, our investment in the project is 100 units

09:07.200 --> 09:11.200
The profitability index gives us 130%

09:12.200 --> 09:16.200
The rule of application is very simple

09:16.200 --> 09:21.200
If the index is greater than 1, we accept the project, if it is less, we reject it

09:21.200 --> 09:26.200
If it is greater than 1, it means that the NPV is greater than 0

09:26.200 --> 09:29.200
If it is less than 1, it means that the NPV is less than 0

09:29.200 --> 09:36.200
There are situations when you compare different projects, but with different amounts

09:37.200 --> 09:42.200
The profitability index allows you to move away from absolute numbers and move to relative numbers

09:42.200 --> 09:48.200
Now about the internal profitability rate

09:48.200 --> 09:50.200
This is the next slide

